    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix thread resource leak in VNF MAC layer cleanup\n\n### Summary\nThe VNF MAC layer implementation had a critical resource management issue where the rx_thread would continue running after mac_destroy() was called, causing thread and socket resource leaks. This led to inconsistent behavior between protocol layers and potential system resource exhaustion under sustained operation.\n\nThis fix implements proper thread termination signaling and resource cleanup in the MAC layer destroy function.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/vnf_sim/src/mac.cpp`: \n  - Added volatile stop_thread flag for thread termination signaling\n  - Added mac_rx_thread field to track thread ID\n  - Modified mac_create() to initialize all fields properly\n  - Updated mac_rx_thread_start() to check termination flag\n  - Enhanced mac_destroy() with comprehensive resource cleanup including thread joining and socket closure\n  - Fixed socket cleanup in error paths\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the original issue:\n1. Run VNF simulation with continuous MAC layer initialization/destruction cycles\n2. Monitor system for thread count growth using 'ps -T -p <pid>'\n3. Observe socket file descriptor leaks using 'lsof -p <pid>'\n4. Notice inconsistent behavior in downstream protocol layers after repeated MAC destroy/create cycles\n\nThe symptoms include gradual thread accumulation, socket resource exhaustion, and unpredictable behavior in NFAPI message handling.\n"
}